Right now, the real world uses are unlimited, but the 
following use cases can really help people out for various
tasks. This is in addition to the usecases of XML/JSON which
can be easily applied to DOT format.

FYI: This DOT format is free and in public domain.

CURRENT USECASES
================
As the DOT format is not popular as of now, this document 
can basically give you some idea on where to use this file
format. The DOT format can effectively replace XML, but here
are some usecases where in XML/JSON could be immediately 
replaced.

1. Storing XML/HTML in SOURCE Control
-------------------------------------
One of the biggest problems with XML/HTML is merging files,
in source control. The way to fix this issue is to store the
information as DOT file and then convert it to XML/HTML.
Or, use DOT itself.

2. Patching XML/HTML
--------------------
Ever tried to patch XML/HTML without using a DOM parser ?
Well, it wasn't designed to be used for patch command.

3. Parsing DOT CLOB in Database
-------------------------------
CLOB has been there in database for quite some time, but
SQL search within CLOB is hard even if it is stored in XML
or for that matter JSON. In both these document format the
whole file needs to be parsed. Or SAX parser has to be used
in the case of XML.
Instead if DOT was used, all that needs to be done is to 
read the line with the appropriate depth speeding up the 
whole process.

Example:
An SQL statement incorporating DOT could be something like 
this:

SELECT name FROM people WHERE people.clobinfo.datatype == 
"DOT" AND people.clobinfo.element == "notthoughtofinfo4" AND
people.clobinfo.elementdepth == 4 && people.clobinfo.element
parents == "peopleinfo,extrainfo,familyinfo";

This could also be done in XML/JSON, but the search will 
be  a lot slower than using DOT file format.

4. Replace generic resource file in IDEs
----------------------------------------
Its lightweight, and it supports appending binary data with 
minimal amount of effort.

5. Use in embedded environment:
-------------------------------
In embedded environment space matters, libxml2 is very large
and libjson-c is small, but DOT's selling point is it provides
XML like hierarchical structure with attributes etc and is 
extremely small in size.

6. Use in configuration files:
------------------------------
Lets say we need to make changes to configuration of an app,
in the case of XML/JSON, you probably need to presupport profiles
or array of configurations. In DOT all one needs to do is append
changes to delete attributes/nodes/elements and create new ones
in place of it.

7. Use in HTML editors:
-----------------------
Don't store HTML/XML, instead convert it and store it in DOT. 
DOT supports multiple Root elements. The entire set of webpages 
can be stored in a single DOT format file. Changes can just be
appended to it. Imagine, only at the time of deployment you need
to convert it back to HTML/XML.

8. Use in GUI IDEs:
-------------------
UI design is generally stored using XML, Here we are considering
only Glade and Qt Designer opensource products. If your project
needs Source Control and it most likely will read point 1.
